    "content_hash": "sha256:481bcf2f570f339f5e2ad8c14a07ed8443cd6579a801f49d66fa6aa69c2336a3",
    "summary": "The Russo-Persian Wars (1722–1828 AD) were a series of conflicts between the expanding Russian Empire and Persia (under successive [[event:2338|Safavid]], [[event:3238|Afsharid]], and [[event:3239|Qajar]] dynasties) for control of the Caucasus region and the Caspian littoral — a century of intermittent warfare that ultimately resulted in Russia's acquisition of most of the Caucasus and the transformation of Persia from a significant regional power into a state on the defensive against European encroachment. The first major war was [[event:2349|Peter the Great's]] Persian campaign (1722–1723), which seized the Caspian provinces as Persia was weakened by internal disorder and Afghan invasion — though Russia returned these provinces in treaties of the 1730s when focus shifted elsewhere.\n\nThe decisive phase came in the early 19th century: the Russo-Persian War of 1804–1813 resulted in the Treaty of Gulistan, ceding most of the modern Republic of Azerbaijan, Dagestan, and Georgia to Russia; the subsequent war of 1826–1828 ended in the Treaty of Turkmenchay, ceding additional Caucasian territories including the areas of modern Armenia and further parts of Azerbaijan. These treaties imposed extraterritoriality provisions on Russian subjects in Persia and fixed the Araxes River as the permanent boundary — the line that separates Iran from the South Caucasus republics today. The Turkmenchay treaty became a symbol of national humiliation for Iranians, and its unfavorable commercial clauses constrained Persian economic development for decades. The wars established Russia as the dominant power in the Caucasus and created the geopolitical framework for the 'Great Game' competition with Britain over Persia and Central Asia.",
